        "$:/plugins/twpub/e8801f1d959ec96b/text/000001955": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/e8801f1d959ec96b/text/000001955",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-e8801f1d959ec96b-0371ff twpub-e8801f1d959ec96b-05227b twpub-e8801f1d959ec96b-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"chapter\"><p>(*9) The <i>Myrmeleon</i>—lion-ant. The term “monster” is equally applicable to small abnormal things and to great, while such epithets as “vast” are merely comparative. The cavern of the myrmeleon is vast in comparison with the hole of the common red ant. A grain of silex is also a “rock.”</p></div></div>"
        },
